WEBVTT

00:05.072 --> 00:08.207
(motor running)

00:08.209 --> 00:13.011
JOHNNY: But right at the mouth
of this channel is

00:13.013 --> 00:17.683
very swift current because
the water's extremely shallow,

00:17.685 --> 00:22.487
and you come in at low tide
to navigate that channel.

00:22.489 --> 00:25.491
And you can see, it's just,
it's just ripping right there.

00:25.493 --> 00:28.494
Nature ultimately dictates
when I have to come out here

00:28.496 --> 00:29.895
and go fishing.

00:29.897 --> 00:31.830
Today I'm gonna go
dip-netting for salmon.

00:31.832 --> 00:34.033
It doesn't matter what
I got going on in my life,

00:34.035 --> 00:35.767
as soon as I know
the salmon are running,

00:35.769 --> 00:37.369
you drop everything,
get out there,

00:37.371 --> 00:41.173
and get your season's
worth of salmon.

00:41.175 --> 00:45.377
The waves hit the sandbar,

00:45.379 --> 00:50.049
and it's very easy to get
your boat full of water.

00:50.051 --> 00:54.186
You know, people,
people died doing this.

00:54.188 --> 00:56.955
They were in a small boat
like, just like mine.

00:59.193 --> 01:01.060
You can see
these waves right here,

01:01.062 --> 01:05.164
and you want to kind of
get in through them without--

01:07.601 --> 01:09.134
Oh, man.

01:09.136 --> 01:15.340
♪ ♪

01:15.342 --> 01:18.877
I just took on
a (bleep) ton of water.

01:18.879 --> 01:19.778
(laughs)

01:21.949 --> 01:24.216
Adventures, man,
that's what it's all about.

01:24.218 --> 01:29.421
♪ ♪

01:29.423 --> 01:35.427
♪ ♪

01:35.429 --> 01:38.630
It's simple to just look
at nature, listen to nature,

01:38.632 --> 01:40.098
read the signs.

01:40.100 --> 01:41.834
It's good to see them
all congregated

01:41.836 --> 01:45.036
in large pods, large groups.

01:45.038 --> 01:47.639
They wouldn't be doing that
if there wasn't food source.

01:47.641 --> 01:50.375
So now it's my time
to come out here

01:50.377 --> 01:52.644
and take advantage
of that bounty.

01:52.646 --> 01:54.913
It's red salmon,
and that's what I'm after.

01:54.915 --> 02:00.519
♪ ♪

02:00.521 --> 02:04.590
I got to get closer over there.
You can see the darker water.

02:04.592 --> 02:07.859
I can feel the prop
getting close to the ground,

02:07.861 --> 02:10.061
and I don't want
to damage my prop.

02:10.063 --> 02:16.468
♪ ♪

02:16.470 --> 02:18.604
I'm starting to get
real shallow.

02:20.541 --> 02:23.275
About two and a half feet deep.

02:23.277 --> 02:28.747
♪ ♪

02:28.749 --> 02:34.820
♪ ♪

02:34.822 --> 02:36.421
Oh, (bleep).

02:39.026 --> 02:41.226
I'm about to hit that bottom.

02:41.228 --> 02:43.228
♪ ♪

02:43.230 --> 02:49.168
♪ ♪

02:49.170 --> 02:52.371
There we go. That keeps
the prop a little higher,

02:52.373 --> 02:54.639
a little bit more
out of the water.

02:54.641 --> 02:59.244
♪ ♪

02:59.246 --> 03:00.979
CHEVIE: You just can't
have a department store

03:00.981 --> 03:03.582
drop off lumber
at your front porch.

03:03.584 --> 03:04.916
I had to cut the trees.

03:04.918 --> 03:06.652
I had to get the trees
back to Shageluk.

03:06.654 --> 03:10.305
It's a lot of hard work
and planning to get it done.

03:10.307 --> 03:14.726
♪ ♪

03:14.728 --> 03:17.329
♪ ♪

03:17.331 --> 03:19.264
I'm at my remote cabin.

03:19.266 --> 03:23.202
I'm here just getting ready
for some fall projects.

03:23.204 --> 03:26.338
And that birch tree over there
is a prime location

03:26.340 --> 03:29.474
for a multiuse tree stand.

03:29.476 --> 03:33.345
We're gonna use it
for a tree fort/tree stand,

03:33.347 --> 03:35.480
just a place to be able
to get up high,

03:35.482 --> 03:36.815
look out on the country,

03:36.817 --> 03:39.017
and see what's out there
when we're hunting.

03:39.019 --> 03:42.020
So I better get after it,
'cause moose season's coming,

03:42.022 --> 03:45.624
and shortly after that,
the snow's gonna start flying.

03:48.228 --> 03:50.762
All right. All the building
material's at the cabin.

03:50.764 --> 03:52.497
I feel good about that.

03:52.499 --> 03:55.433
Number-one thing to do is
to start cutting some of this,

03:55.435 --> 03:58.169
all this grass down
so I have good visibility

03:58.171 --> 04:01.406
and a safe working space.

04:01.408 --> 04:03.241
(starts weed trimmer)

04:03.243 --> 04:06.978
We're gonna get this project
done and get it done right.

04:06.980 --> 04:09.648
I want to get this project
done lickety-split

04:09.650 --> 04:12.851
and be able to use it
for this hunting season.

04:12.853 --> 04:13.719
I'm gonna be sitting up there

04:13.721 --> 04:15.587
with my kids looking
for big bull moose,

04:15.589 --> 04:16.722
and they're gonna be asking me

04:16.724 --> 04:18.790
10,000 questions
like another day

04:18.792 --> 04:21.393
except for we're gonna be
ten feet off the ground.

04:21.395 --> 04:24.796
(weed trimmer stops)

04:24.798 --> 04:26.732
All right. Got some
weed whacking done.

04:26.734 --> 04:28.934
And that tree stand's
right here behind us.

04:28.936 --> 04:30.936
It's gonna be up off the ground.

04:30.938 --> 04:36.208
All out here, I'm looking
for moose and just anything.

04:36.210 --> 04:39.277
This is what I'm looking
to see more of. Cool.

04:39.279 --> 04:41.413
Time to get some work done.

04:41.415 --> 04:45.750
♪ ♪

04:45.752 --> 04:48.286
KALEB: Out here, we have
the freedom whenever we want

04:48.288 --> 04:51.890
to go out and learn a life
lesson, to just go do it.

04:51.892 --> 04:54.159
There's no hindrances
that get in the way

04:54.161 --> 04:58.096
of learning how to survive
in the middle of the wilderness.

04:58.098 --> 05:01.766
♪ ♪

05:01.768 --> 05:04.102
♪ ♪

05:04.104 --> 05:09.240
♪ ♪

05:09.242 --> 05:12.444
This rain is gonna make
everything challenging.

05:12.446 --> 05:14.846
Right now, I've got
four cords of wood

05:14.848 --> 05:18.317
just piled up in my yard,
and it's raining right now.

05:18.319 --> 05:20.185
The wood is soaking wet.

05:20.187 --> 05:22.054
I couldn't light a fire
with my firewood

05:22.056 --> 05:24.055
if I wanted to right now,

05:24.057 --> 05:27.259
so I need a way to protect it
and keep it dry.

05:27.261 --> 05:29.194
I harvested this tree
last winter.

05:29.196 --> 05:32.464
And now, I need to get it
sized up, cut up,

05:32.466 --> 05:34.599
all the important stuff.

05:34.601 --> 05:37.469
And, uh, next thing you know,
it'll be standing up

05:37.471 --> 05:40.539
and we'll be keeping
the rain off my firewood.

05:40.541 --> 05:41.740
BRITTANY: Hey.
KALEB: Hi.

05:41.742 --> 05:43.275
BRITTANY: You got
some marks going on.

05:43.277 --> 05:45.277
KALEB: Yeah. I'm getting
the first one ready

05:45.279 --> 05:48.880
for some chainsawing.

05:48.882 --> 05:50.215
BRITTANY: I think we're
really gonna appreciate

05:50.217 --> 05:54.686
this woodshed come winter
and we have actually dry wood.

05:54.688 --> 05:57.155
KALEB: Oh, yeah.
I am so looking forward to that.

05:57.157 --> 05:59.891
Dry wood. No ice stuck to it.

05:59.893 --> 06:02.227
No pools of water
on our floor from the ice.

06:02.229 --> 06:03.228
BRITTANY: No kidding.

06:03.230 --> 06:05.097
KALEB: Thawing out.

06:05.099 --> 06:06.831
It'll be very nice.

06:06.833 --> 06:09.634
(chainsaw buzzing)

06:09.636 --> 06:10.969
BRITTANY: When it's
fall time around here,

06:10.971 --> 06:12.704
our priorities have to change.

06:12.706 --> 06:17.308
We need to focus on what is
going to happen this winter.

06:17.310 --> 06:19.110
Every winter it's very cold,

06:19.112 --> 06:22.046
which means we need to make sure
we have plenty of wood

06:22.048 --> 06:25.316
and we need a really great
place to keep it dry.

06:25.318 --> 06:27.786
We can't wait
for the sun to shine.

06:27.788 --> 06:30.054
We need to get this done now.

06:30.056 --> 06:34.259
♪ ♪

06:34.261 --> 06:35.594
It's like sharpening
a really big pencil.

06:35.596 --> 06:37.279
KALEB: A very, very big pencil.

06:37.281 --> 06:38.263
For Paul Bunyan.

06:38.265 --> 06:39.397
BRITTANY: Mm-hmm.

06:39.399 --> 06:43.001
KALEB: Let's drag this,
drag this over into place.

06:43.003 --> 06:45.470
This'll be the first rear post.

06:45.472 --> 06:46.538
BRITTANY: Okay.

06:46.540 --> 06:48.073
KALEB: So we're gonna get
all the posts into place,

06:48.075 --> 06:51.610
and then we'll stand 'em
all up at once.

06:51.612 --> 06:52.477
BRITTANY: So, which one?

06:52.479 --> 06:53.812
KALEB: We'll go
to the back corner there

06:53.814 --> 06:55.680
and work our way forwards.

06:55.682 --> 06:59.484
♪ ♪

06:59.486 --> 07:01.253
Oh, doggo.

07:04.090 --> 07:08.760
We'll just lay it there,
and we'll build the next one.

07:08.762 --> 07:10.161
Huh, that worked out good.

07:10.163 --> 07:11.162
BRITTANY: Cool.

07:11.164 --> 07:15.700
KALEB: Looks nice.
Let's get the next one out.

07:15.702 --> 07:18.369
Time is not something
that I can get back.

07:18.371 --> 07:22.640
If I don't use these
resources, these logs,

07:22.642 --> 07:24.642
I let them rot into the ground,

07:24.644 --> 07:27.512
that's several days of my life
that I'll never get back.

07:27.514 --> 07:30.915
I'm not gonna let
a resource go to waste.

07:30.917 --> 07:33.585
BRITTANY: Woo-hoo!
Last pencil down!

07:33.587 --> 07:35.920
KALEB: I think
that's my best cut yet.

07:35.922 --> 07:36.988
BRITTANY: Let's move this over.

07:36.990 --> 07:37.922
KALEB: Yep. Let's
get this over there

07:37.924 --> 07:40.725
and call it quits
for a little bit.

07:40.727 --> 07:42.193
I'm tuckered.

07:42.195 --> 07:44.462
BRITTANY: Let's move it over
and move on to the next phase.

07:44.464 --> 07:47.866
KALEB: Yeah. Next, we have
to stand these things up

07:47.868 --> 07:51.002
and brace 'em off.

07:51.004 --> 07:51.870
BRITTANY: Okay.

07:51.872 --> 07:53.738
KALEB: All right, last piece.

07:53.740 --> 07:56.541
BRITTANY: Man, that was fun.

07:56.543 --> 07:57.342
KALEB: A lot of work.

07:57.344 --> 07:58.877
(laughs)

07:58.879 --> 08:03.815
♪ ♪

08:03.817 --> 08:07.402
JESSI: A lot of people measure
success totally different.

08:07.404 --> 08:09.554
For a lot of people,
it might be a big house

08:09.556 --> 08:13.225
or a big family
or a big bank account.

08:13.227 --> 08:14.425
But for me, it's the knowledge

08:14.427 --> 08:16.161
that I'm learning
from this land.

08:18.432 --> 08:20.098
All right, you ready?

08:20.100 --> 08:21.833
CHRIS: Yeah, I'm ready.

08:21.835 --> 08:24.168
JESSI: And we're off.

08:24.170 --> 08:27.072
CHRIS: Let's go fishing.
JESSI: Let's go fishing.

08:29.643 --> 08:30.975
CHRIS: We're headed
to where it's rippling.

08:30.977 --> 08:32.911
That should be where
the water's mixing.

08:32.913 --> 08:35.780
This water's a little murky
for fishing with a rod and reel.

08:35.782 --> 08:37.448
So once we get into
that less murky water,

08:37.450 --> 08:39.250
we should be able to fish.

08:39.252 --> 08:41.519
This is gonna be great.

08:41.521 --> 08:43.655
JESSI: All winter,
we didn't have fish.

08:43.657 --> 08:45.924
We didn't have anything.

08:45.926 --> 08:48.860
And so we need to start
thinking about next season.

08:48.862 --> 08:52.063
If we can get a huge stockpile
of fish this summer,

08:52.065 --> 08:55.266
that makes winter
so much easier.

08:55.268 --> 08:59.871
♪ ♪

08:59.873 --> 09:01.540
All right,
we are on the sandbar.

09:01.542 --> 09:03.541
CHRIS: Perfect. That's exactly
where we want to be.

09:03.543 --> 09:05.477
So check this out.
Right where it's mixing,

09:05.479 --> 09:08.346
we're gonna cast
right out this way and reel in,

09:08.348 --> 09:10.282
and we've got the fish that are
coming up from the Tanana,

09:10.284 --> 09:12.283
and they're eating right
in this little spot here.

09:12.285 --> 09:13.685
We don't want to cast
into the murky

09:13.687 --> 09:17.422
'cause they wouldn't
be able to see our lure.

09:17.424 --> 09:18.490
JESSI: All right.

09:18.492 --> 09:20.492
Here's the spot.

09:22.296 --> 09:25.430
CHRIS: All right.
Here is a frog,

09:25.432 --> 09:27.966
if you want to try fishing
with this frog for now.

09:27.968 --> 09:31.703
Or actually,
I think it's a mouse.

09:31.705 --> 09:35.039
JESSI: This is
gonna work just fine.

09:35.041 --> 09:36.441
The day fishing season ends,

09:36.443 --> 09:38.710
I'm looking forward
to the next fishing season.

09:38.712 --> 09:40.979
I don't care if it rains,
if it pours, it's thunder,

09:40.981 --> 09:43.715
it's wind, it's lightning,
hurricane, I don't care.

09:43.717 --> 09:45.617
I am here for the fish.

09:47.054 --> 09:49.721
(thunder)

09:49.723 --> 09:53.391
(rain falling)

09:53.393 --> 09:54.726
JESSI: That's weird.

09:54.728 --> 09:58.997
CHRIS: There's trees down there.
I'm catching leaves.

09:58.999 --> 10:00.165
JESSI: Ooh.

10:03.003 --> 10:04.603
Oh, my God. Put your stuff down.

10:04.605 --> 10:06.137
There's a black bear
right there.

10:06.139 --> 10:09.474
There's a black
bear right there.

10:09.476 --> 10:11.309
He's coming towards us.

10:21.488 --> 10:22.887
JESSI: He just came down
at the trees,

10:22.889 --> 10:24.355
and he's slowly making
his way towards us.

10:24.357 --> 10:25.490
CHRIS: Tozitna,
you stay in this boat.

10:25.492 --> 10:27.025
JESSI: Do you want me
to get her leash?

10:27.027 --> 10:28.226
CHRIS: Yeah, may as well.
JESSI: Yeah? Okay.

10:28.228 --> 10:29.293
CHRIS: I don't think
there's gonna be a problem,

10:29.295 --> 10:31.029
but I don't want,
if that bear runs across here,

10:31.031 --> 10:32.347
I don't want there to be.

10:32.349 --> 10:34.499
JESSI: Can you put that on her?

10:34.501 --> 10:36.901
(whining)

10:36.903 --> 10:41.973
♪ ♪

10:41.975 --> 10:42.974
Is that making noises?

10:42.976 --> 10:43.841
(whining)

10:43.843 --> 10:44.776
No, that's our dog.

10:44.778 --> 10:45.643
CHRIS: Hey!

10:45.645 --> 10:46.911
(dog whining)

10:46.913 --> 10:50.649
Hey! Go on!

10:50.651 --> 10:52.784
JESSI: There he goes
disappearing into the trees.

10:52.786 --> 10:54.452
(dog whining)

10:54.454 --> 10:56.521
CHRIS: I'm gonna
get back to fishing.

10:56.523 --> 10:57.522
JESSI: You're okay, Toze.

10:57.524 --> 10:59.491
You're with me.
It's gonna be okay.

11:02.128 --> 11:03.595
You're very good.

11:03.597 --> 11:04.596
(whine)

11:04.598 --> 11:07.131
I know.

11:07.133 --> 11:11.236
The Cosna knows how to liven up
a dreary day of fishing.

11:13.073 --> 11:15.140
This place is rife with bears.

11:15.142 --> 11:17.809
If we've seen this bear
and he came this close,

11:17.811 --> 11:19.811
then there's some more
that we haven't seen.

11:19.813 --> 11:21.146
We need to be alert.

11:21.148 --> 11:25.684
♪ ♪

11:25.686 --> 11:26.684
CHRIS: Oh, I got
snagged up again.

11:26.686 --> 11:28.953
We got to get out of this area.

11:28.955 --> 11:32.357
JESSI: Yeah, just start,
stop going that way.

11:32.359 --> 11:33.358
CHRIS: Oh. No, that's a fish.

11:33.360 --> 11:34.292
JESSI: A fish?

11:34.294 --> 11:35.243
CHRIS: A big fish.

11:35.245 --> 11:37.428
JESSI: Ah! Yes!

11:37.430 --> 11:40.098
Ah! Oh, my gosh!

11:40.100 --> 11:40.899
CHRIS: Take me to shore.

11:40.901 --> 11:41.983
JESSI: I'm going!

11:41.985 --> 11:43.034
CHRIS: I'm trying
not to lose it.

11:43.036 --> 11:44.235
JESSI: Okay, I'm trying!

11:44.237 --> 11:45.303
CHRIS: It's going under the
boat. It's going under the boat.

11:45.305 --> 11:46.371
JESSI: What do you
want me to do?

11:46.373 --> 11:47.238
We're coming in.

11:47.240 --> 11:49.440
CHRIS: Oh, it's
pulling on me hard.

11:49.442 --> 11:53.978
I'm gonna just bring him up.
Take the dog.

11:53.980 --> 11:56.981
Let me come up onto shore.
Ooh, he's fighting me.

11:56.983 --> 11:58.783
He's too big to bring
into the canoe.

11:58.785 --> 12:00.852
JESSI: Okay.

12:00.854 --> 12:02.654
CHRIS: I need you
to grab the fish.

12:02.656 --> 12:04.388
JESSI: Okay.

12:04.390 --> 12:05.990
CHRIS: Look at
this sheefish, man.

12:05.992 --> 12:06.991
JESSI: Is that what this is?

12:06.993 --> 12:07.792
CHRIS: Yeah.

12:07.794 --> 12:08.860
JESSI: Can I put my hand here?

12:08.862 --> 12:09.861
CHRIS: Bring it up by the gill.
This is great.

12:09.863 --> 12:10.929
Don't let the dog get in there.

12:10.931 --> 12:13.397
JESSI: Tozie.

12:13.399 --> 12:15.200
CHRIS: Awesome fish, Jess!

12:15.202 --> 12:16.267
Look at that!

12:16.269 --> 12:18.403
JESSI: Yeah!
CHRIS: Ha ha ha ha!

12:18.405 --> 12:20.672
That's a beautiful fish.

12:20.674 --> 12:24.609
♪ ♪

12:24.611 --> 12:27.212
KALEB: Out here, the willingness
to roll with the punches

12:27.214 --> 12:29.413
is of the utmost importance.

12:29.415 --> 12:31.616
It's no reason
to change my plans.

12:31.618 --> 12:34.485
It's just I got to deal
with what's thrown at me

12:34.487 --> 12:38.423
the best way I know how
and continue to get my job done.

12:40.360 --> 12:42.293
BRITTANY: Okay.
What's the next phase?

12:42.295 --> 12:44.762
KALEB: Oh, it's time to get
these logs stood up.

12:44.764 --> 12:45.897
BRITTANY: Fantastic.

12:45.899 --> 12:47.632
KALEB: Start here
and work our way back.

12:47.634 --> 12:49.234
Oh, yeah.

12:49.236 --> 12:54.239
♪ ♪

12:54.241 --> 12:56.841
Look at that.
First corner post is up.

12:56.843 --> 12:58.042
BRITTANY: Woo-hoo.

12:58.044 --> 13:03.114
KALEB: Get it kind of centered
in the, those marks there.

13:03.116 --> 13:04.248
I'm liking how this looks.

13:04.250 --> 13:05.717
All right, now
don't let it fall over.

13:05.719 --> 13:06.717
I'm gonna grab a brace.

13:06.719 --> 13:08.119
BRITTANY: All right.

13:08.121 --> 13:11.189
Man, the rain's picked up.

13:11.191 --> 13:13.391
KALEB: Let's see
if this is long enough.

13:13.393 --> 13:18.530
Ooh, we'll just go to the bottom
of that tree to this tree.

13:18.532 --> 13:21.265
Perfect.

13:21.267 --> 13:22.534
BRITTANY:
Don't shoot me, please.

13:22.536 --> 13:23.935
(whir)

13:23.937 --> 13:29.874
♪ ♪

13:29.876 --> 13:30.642
(whir)

13:32.545 --> 13:33.344
Can I let go now?

13:33.346 --> 13:36.013
KALEB: Yeah, now you can let go.

13:36.015 --> 13:37.815
BRITTANY:
Look at that. One more.

13:37.817 --> 13:39.217
So, what's the next?

13:39.219 --> 13:41.552
KALEB: Oh, we'll just
keep standing 'em up.

13:41.554 --> 13:44.422
BRITTANY: Okay.

13:44.424 --> 13:46.291
KALEB: These logs that
I've collected will become

13:46.293 --> 13:48.626
the corner posts
for the building.

13:48.628 --> 13:49.894
There's six of them.

13:49.896 --> 13:51.829
And these logs
will support a purlin,

13:51.831 --> 13:53.298
which is a horizontal member

13:53.300 --> 13:55.766
that supports
the weight of the roof.

13:55.768 --> 13:58.169
It will be a team effort

13:58.171 --> 14:02.173
to get these logs vertical
and in place.

14:02.175 --> 14:04.375
Oof!

14:04.377 --> 14:05.376
Hey.

14:05.378 --> 14:07.579
♪ ♪

14:07.581 --> 14:12.784
♪ ♪

14:12.786 --> 14:16.053
All right, look out.

14:16.055 --> 14:18.723
BRITTANY: Last one. Woo-hoo!

14:18.725 --> 14:20.258
KALEB: Once these posts
are vertical,

14:20.260 --> 14:21.726
they need to be braced off.

14:21.728 --> 14:23.728
If I don't brace them off,
they'll fall over,

14:23.730 --> 14:26.064
squish somebody,
cause a broken leg,

14:26.066 --> 14:28.633
or some other form
of extreme pain.

14:32.339 --> 14:36.274
Okay, shoot it off down there.

14:36.276 --> 14:37.208
Whoa, careful.

14:37.210 --> 14:38.276
BRITTANY: Yep. Yep.

14:38.278 --> 14:39.744
KALEB: Don't be doing that.

14:39.746 --> 14:41.346
BRITTANY: I realized
that afterwards.

14:41.348 --> 14:43.748
KALEB: That would have been bad.

14:43.750 --> 14:46.951
Braces keep things
from falling over.

14:46.953 --> 14:48.353
Yeah, that's pretty good.

14:48.355 --> 14:51.689
♪ ♪

14:51.691 --> 14:54.826
Once I have the posts stood
and I get 'em braced off,

14:54.828 --> 14:56.294
they're solid.

14:56.296 --> 14:58.696
For my purlins,
I have random pieces of 2x8

14:58.698 --> 15:01.365
scattered around my property
that I gather up

15:01.367 --> 15:05.003
and cut 'em to length and nail
'em to the top of the posts.

15:07.774 --> 15:11.509
Man, this is gonna
be a good woodshed!

15:11.511 --> 15:15.847
No!

15:15.849 --> 15:17.315
Out of batteries.

15:17.317 --> 15:21.135
♪ ♪

15:21.137 --> 15:26.991
♪ ♪

15:26.993 --> 15:29.193
Like, you'd think by now,

15:29.195 --> 15:32.797
us dumb carpenters would know
better and we'd check our nails

15:32.799 --> 15:35.266
before we went up
to a spot like this.

15:35.268 --> 15:40.672
♪ ♪

15:40.674 --> 15:41.472
Ooh!

15:48.298 --> 15:49.097
KALEB: Ooh!

15:49.099 --> 15:50.231
(thump)

15:50.233 --> 15:53.501
That's a situation where
you just let go of it.

15:53.503 --> 15:55.603
No sense going with it.

15:58.441 --> 15:59.573
(nail gun fires)

15:59.575 --> 16:03.244
I got my purlins done,
posts standed up,

16:03.246 --> 16:05.847
now my roof rafters are cut and
it's time to get them all in.

16:05.849 --> 16:08.650
I lost my help, so I'm
gonna have to struggle

16:08.652 --> 16:10.985
with these by myself.

16:10.987 --> 16:13.854
These rafters tie the two halves
of the building together

16:13.856 --> 16:16.724
and provide a structure
to put my roof on.

16:16.726 --> 16:18.592
Without the structure,
there's no roof,

16:18.594 --> 16:21.462
and with no roof, there's no way
to keep my firewood dry,

16:21.464 --> 16:25.867
so this is a very important step
in building this woodshed.

16:29.472 --> 16:31.739
All right, these rafters are on.

16:31.741 --> 16:34.475
BRITTANY: Wow, you got busy.

16:34.477 --> 16:37.679
KALEB: Yeah. You abandoned me.

16:37.681 --> 16:39.614
BRITTANY: I had to take care
of your children.

16:39.616 --> 16:40.648
KALEB: Oh.

16:42.752 --> 16:44.218
BRITTANY: Well, check that out.

16:44.220 --> 16:46.020
KALEB: Yeah, I think
our structure's done.

16:46.022 --> 16:47.088
BRITTANY: This is amazing.

16:47.090 --> 16:49.357
KALEB: Next thing we need to do
is put sheeting on

16:49.359 --> 16:50.425
and roof this sucker.

16:50.427 --> 16:51.559
BRITTANY: Cool.

16:51.561 --> 16:53.361
KALEB: Hopefully it's not
raining when we do that, though,

16:53.363 --> 16:58.499
'cause slippery roofing
equals falling carpenters.

16:58.501 --> 16:59.834
BRITTANY: Let's not be
falling carpenters.

16:59.836 --> 17:02.236
KALEB: And I'd prefer not
to be a falling carpenter.

17:02.238 --> 17:06.774
♪ ♪

17:06.776 --> 17:08.443
JOHNNY: Having
subsistence opportunity

17:08.445 --> 17:09.844
is really important for me.

17:09.846 --> 17:10.912
You can buy your food,

17:10.914 --> 17:12.246
or you can go out
and you can find your food,

17:12.248 --> 17:15.116
and I prefer to come out here
and find my own food.

17:16.652 --> 17:17.985
(grunting)

17:20.790 --> 17:25.726
Ooh, man, Java, you got better
four-wheel drive than me.

17:25.728 --> 17:26.861
As an Alaskan resident,

17:26.863 --> 17:29.797
we're allowed to
subsistence-fish for salmon,

17:29.799 --> 17:32.400
but each location
has a method of take.

17:32.402 --> 17:36.537
And at this location, the best
way to do it is with a dip net.

17:36.539 --> 17:40.341
This is a little fall
right here, and there's a pool.

17:40.343 --> 17:42.143
And the fish will gather
in this pool,

17:42.145 --> 17:46.080
reserve their energy to come up
either side of this fall.

17:46.082 --> 17:48.282
So while they're
kind of resting,

17:48.284 --> 17:51.619
that's where I scoop
and catch a bunch of fish.

17:51.621 --> 17:55.556
♪ ♪

17:55.558 --> 17:59.360
Sockeye salmon are the fish that
I'll be catching in this creek.

17:59.362 --> 18:01.763
They grill nicely,
they cook nicely.

18:01.765 --> 18:03.564
Most importantly,
they dry really well,

18:03.566 --> 18:05.800
which is probably what
I'll be doing with these fish.

18:08.705 --> 18:11.038
There we go.

18:11.040 --> 18:13.307
That's two.

18:13.309 --> 18:15.777
Oh, I got a twofer.

18:15.779 --> 18:19.914
Look at that.
This is what I'm after.

18:19.916 --> 18:21.716
Look how tired they are.

18:23.920 --> 18:27.789
Sockeye salmon,
also known as reds.

18:27.791 --> 18:30.391
We call them reds up here.
And when you catch them,

18:30.393 --> 18:33.127
the first thing you got to do
is clip their tail.

18:33.129 --> 18:38.732
You got to cut
the end of the tail off.

18:38.734 --> 18:41.669
And that way, if Fish and Game
comes, they'll see that

18:41.671 --> 18:44.405
and they'll know that I'm
a subsistence resident fisher

18:44.407 --> 18:47.074
of this subsistence fishing run.

18:47.076 --> 18:50.144
My little stinky fish bag.

18:50.146 --> 18:52.814
It's only used for this purpose.

18:52.816 --> 18:54.949
All right, so that's
the first fish done.

18:54.951 --> 18:56.150
Gonna take care
of the second fish

18:56.152 --> 18:58.553
because I want to get back
into that pool,

18:58.555 --> 19:02.156
'cause apparently
the salmon are running.

19:02.158 --> 19:06.360
Into the basket he goes.

19:06.362 --> 19:09.497
There we go, that's two fish.

19:09.499 --> 19:12.700
We got a ways to go.

19:12.702 --> 19:14.902
Most locations in Alaska
have salmon.

19:14.904 --> 19:17.305
My Arctic location
does not have salmon,

19:17.307 --> 19:19.240
so when I'm
at my summer location,

19:19.242 --> 19:21.042
the goal is to catch
as many as I can

19:21.044 --> 19:23.310
in a short window of time.

19:23.312 --> 19:26.847
There we go. Getting
some weight in there.

19:26.849 --> 19:28.983
Getting all these salmon
is a win-win

19:28.985 --> 19:30.851
'cause it's gonna
supply me with a lot of food

19:30.853 --> 19:32.786
and it's gonna supply me
with trapping bait

19:32.788 --> 19:34.422
for my camp up North.

19:37.393 --> 19:39.927
I don't know, man, it kind of
slowed down right here.

19:42.665 --> 19:45.332
I think I'm gonna
hike up a little bit.

19:45.334 --> 19:49.069
There's a good spot further up.

19:49.071 --> 19:50.538
Now, if I keep poking
around with my net

19:50.540 --> 19:51.672
in the same location,

19:51.674 --> 19:53.541
the fish are gonna
catch on to me,

19:53.543 --> 19:57.078
so it's important to kind of
move on, find new locations,

19:57.080 --> 19:59.480
uh, so you don't just
burn out one spot.

19:59.482 --> 20:05.085
♪ ♪

20:05.087 --> 20:06.153
CHEVIE: I think
the most challenging part

20:06.155 --> 20:08.956
about doing this build
is just the logistics.

20:08.958 --> 20:13.561
It's just the thought process
of being a few steps ahead

20:13.563 --> 20:15.429
so you know you can
have a productive day.

20:17.767 --> 20:22.036
All right, you guys,
grab a bucket on your way out.

20:22.038 --> 20:23.771
All right. Well,
it's not raining too bad,

20:23.773 --> 20:25.973
that's kind of,
that's pretty good.

20:25.975 --> 20:27.375
SYDNEY: Yeah, it's good time.

20:27.377 --> 20:28.509
CHEVIE: So my kids
are gonna come out here,

20:28.511 --> 20:30.177
they're gonna help
with all the processes.

20:30.179 --> 20:32.446
They're still pretty little,
so they're gonna be hands-off

20:32.448 --> 20:34.848
with, with a lot
of the heavy lifting.

20:34.850 --> 20:35.716
I told them they could paint

20:35.718 --> 20:37.518
the exterior walls
of the tree stand,

20:37.520 --> 20:40.521
so they're looking forward
to doing that.

20:40.523 --> 20:42.256
All right, let's get
this party started.

20:42.258 --> 20:43.524
RYDER: Yeah!

20:43.526 --> 20:45.526
CHEVIE: So I want you guys to
choose a color, paint with it.

20:45.528 --> 20:46.327
RYDER: Whoa, yellow!

20:46.329 --> 20:47.862
CHEVIE: Whoa, jeez.
Look at that.

20:47.864 --> 20:49.196
RYDER: Yellow!
SYDNEY: Oh, yeah.

20:49.198 --> 20:50.197
CHEVIE: So don't,
try not to get this

20:50.199 --> 20:51.665
all over your hands
and your clothes.

20:51.667 --> 20:52.533
SYDNEY: Okay.

20:52.535 --> 20:53.534
RYDER: Okay.

20:53.536 --> 20:54.335
CHEVIE: We'll see how--

20:54.337 --> 20:55.869
(laughing)

20:55.871 --> 20:57.672
If that's your
favorite sweatshirt,

20:57.674 --> 20:59.006
kiss it goodbye, okay?

20:59.008 --> 21:00.141
(laughing)

21:00.143 --> 21:01.942
Make sure you paint,
whatever color,

21:01.944 --> 21:04.078
you got to paint the whole board
one color first.

21:04.080 --> 21:05.145
Remember like
I've been telling you?

21:05.147 --> 21:06.280
RYDER: Yeah, I know.
SYDNEY: Yeah, yeah, yeah.

21:06.282 --> 21:07.214
CHEVIE: It doesn't
have to be perfect.

21:07.216 --> 21:08.482
This is just for fun, right?

21:08.484 --> 21:09.483
SYDNEY: Yeah.

21:09.485 --> 21:10.751
CHEVIE: This is the way
that I like to teach.

21:10.753 --> 21:13.087
Hand them the tools,
give them some direction,

21:13.089 --> 21:14.422
and then back off.

21:14.424 --> 21:15.957
How's that working, Sydney?

21:15.959 --> 21:16.958
SYDNEY: Cool.

21:16.960 --> 21:18.225
CHEVIE: Cool.

21:18.227 --> 21:20.761
All right. Well, looks like
you guys got it under control.

21:20.763 --> 21:22.830
They're all laughing
and having fun.

21:22.832 --> 21:25.833
As long as I can teach
a few things, it makes me smile.

21:25.835 --> 21:29.303
I get a kick out of it.

21:29.305 --> 21:33.107
Ryder, I need you to help me
with the post-hole digger.

21:33.109 --> 21:37.912
♪ ♪

21:37.914 --> 21:39.446
CHRIS: We're at the mouth
of the Cosna.

21:39.448 --> 21:41.048
I'm really excited
to do some fishing.

21:41.050 --> 21:43.050
This is where I fished
with my dad as a kid.

21:43.052 --> 21:45.186
This is my favorite fishing spot
in all the world.

21:45.188 --> 21:46.153
I love this place.

21:48.124 --> 21:49.123
JESSI: All right, let's head

21:49.125 --> 21:51.191
down the bend a little bit,

21:51.193 --> 21:53.194
try to find some deeper water.

21:53.196 --> 21:54.328
CHRIS: Yeah.

21:54.330 --> 21:56.330
JESSI: It's real shallow
right here on this whole bank.

21:56.332 --> 21:59.266
CHRIS: I'd love to catch a pike.

21:59.268 --> 22:00.668
This is looking better
right in here.

22:00.670 --> 22:03.070
I think I'll stand
right on the end of this.

22:03.072 --> 22:04.538
JESSI: Might be a good spot.

22:04.540 --> 22:07.608
CHRIS: Yeah. Let's just try
this out for a few minutes.

22:07.610 --> 22:08.676
Wow, it's deep right here.

22:08.678 --> 22:09.810
(Jessi chuckles)

22:09.812 --> 22:10.811
I hope I don't catch a big fish,

22:10.813 --> 22:11.945
it'll pull me right off.

22:11.947 --> 22:14.415
JESSI: I hope I get a big fish.

22:14.417 --> 22:17.885
Woo! There's a nice,
big wolfy print right there.

22:17.887 --> 22:21.489
Wow! Fresh wolf print.

22:21.491 --> 22:23.424
Oh, they must have been
tracking a bear or something.

22:23.426 --> 22:27.828
Wow! These bear and wolf prints
are extremely fresh.

22:27.830 --> 22:29.563
This is a really bountiful
place that we're in,

22:29.565 --> 22:30.831
the mouth of the Cosna.

22:30.833 --> 22:32.166
You can see wolf tracks,

22:32.168 --> 22:34.969
you can see beaver,
muskrat, bear.

22:34.971 --> 22:37.038
But, I mean, that's like
a good-sized wolf print.

22:37.040 --> 22:39.306
One going that way
and one going back?

22:39.308 --> 22:41.575
I mean, all of the animals
of the Cosna

22:41.577 --> 22:43.911
have all kind of congregated
right here at the mouth,

22:43.913 --> 22:46.514
so we just need to be alert.

22:49.452 --> 22:50.651
Oh.

22:50.653 --> 22:51.986
CHRIS: Was that a fish jumping?

22:51.988 --> 22:54.388
JESSI: It had to be
because it was up to my left.

22:54.390 --> 22:55.990
CHRIS: Well, maybe we need to
move up to where the weeds are

22:55.992 --> 22:57.057
a little bit more.

22:57.059 --> 22:58.859
It's kind of deep here.

22:58.861 --> 23:00.995
JESSI: I think
I'm in a good spot.

23:00.997 --> 23:03.664
If you come down here, bring,
bring all the mosquito (bleep)

23:03.666 --> 23:04.932
And head nets and stuff.
I'm dying.

23:04.934 --> 23:05.933
CHRIS: Well, then I'm
gonna stay right here.

23:05.935 --> 23:07.268
You enjoy those mosquitos.

23:07.270 --> 23:09.336
JESSI: Ah, sh-nap.

23:09.338 --> 23:12.005
Alaskan mosquitos are
a whole 'nother breed.

23:12.007 --> 23:13.874
They swarm you,
it's like a mist,

23:13.876 --> 23:15.943
and they just come at you,
and it's just incessant.

23:15.945 --> 23:17.211
They never stop.

23:17.213 --> 23:19.480
You try to take a deep breath
and they just fill your lungs,

23:19.482 --> 23:20.414
they attack your throat,

23:20.416 --> 23:21.482
they're trying
to get into your ears,

23:21.484 --> 23:22.750
they're poking into your eyes.

23:22.752 --> 23:25.219
These guys are beasts.

23:25.221 --> 23:26.287
Okay, got to get my stuff.

23:26.289 --> 23:29.123
Hoo ah, hoo ah, hoo ah! Ah!

23:32.228 --> 23:38.766
♪ ♪

23:38.768 --> 23:42.837
Oh, oh, oh, oh, oh, oh, oh,
oh, oh, oh, oh, oh, oh!

23:42.839 --> 23:44.538
Love, love!

23:51.564 --> 23:52.563
CHRIS: Get it, baby!

23:52.565 --> 23:53.898
JESSI: I think I lost it!

23:53.900 --> 23:55.466
I think I lost it!

23:55.468 --> 23:56.767
CHRIS: Did you lose it?

23:56.769 --> 24:00.237
JESSI: I think I lost it!

24:00.239 --> 24:01.672
Damn!

24:04.376 --> 24:06.243
(sigh)

24:06.245 --> 24:08.112
They're out there.

24:08.114 --> 24:09.713
I'm casting and I'm snagging,

24:09.715 --> 24:11.115
and I'm casting
and I'm snagging,

24:11.117 --> 24:12.649
and every time
I go through the weeds,

24:12.651 --> 24:13.984
I just, my heart leaps.

24:13.986 --> 24:14.985
It's a rush.

24:14.987 --> 24:16.454
Every time
that you get a nibble,

24:16.456 --> 24:17.655
you know something's down there,

24:17.657 --> 24:20.057
you just don't know what
you're gonna pull out.

24:20.059 --> 24:25.930
♪ ♪

24:25.932 --> 24:28.732
Oh! Ugh, I had a bite.

24:28.734 --> 24:30.868
Ugh, is that a fish,
or is that a snag?

24:30.870 --> 24:34.605
What is that?

24:34.607 --> 24:35.739
That's a fish.
That's a fish!

24:35.741 --> 24:37.207
Chris! Chris! I think.

24:37.209 --> 24:38.075
CHRIS: You got a fish?

24:38.077 --> 24:40.277
JESSI: I think so!
Maybe! Maybe!

24:40.279 --> 24:41.278
CHRIS: I'm coming, love.

24:41.280 --> 24:42.212
JESSI: It's a fish!
It's a fish!

24:42.214 --> 24:43.080
It's a fish!

24:43.082 --> 24:45.349
CHRIS: Oh,
it's a huge fish, Jess!

24:45.351 --> 24:46.483
I'm coming, Jess!

24:46.485 --> 24:47.618
JESSI: Come here! It's a fish!

24:47.620 --> 24:49.286
I think, is it a sheefish?
What is that?

24:49.288 --> 24:50.621
CHRIS: Easy, easy, easy.

24:50.623 --> 24:53.424
JESSI: Okay.

24:53.426 --> 24:54.558
CHRIS: It's huge!

24:54.560 --> 24:55.492
JESSI: Yeah, yeah.
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

24:55.494 --> 24:57.261
CHRIS: Pull him in.
Right there, love.

24:57.263 --> 24:58.495
There it is.

24:58.497 --> 25:00.230
JESSI: Oh, Chris, don't lose it,
don't lose it, don't lose it.

25:00.232 --> 25:01.031
Please, don't lose it.

25:01.033 --> 25:02.499
CHRIS: I'm trying to--don't!

25:02.501 --> 25:03.567
I got it.

25:06.505 --> 25:07.905
JESSI: Way to go.

25:07.907 --> 25:08.839
This came undone.

25:08.841 --> 25:09.974
CHRIS: It broke.

25:09.976 --> 25:11.775
That's why I just grabbed him
and threw him.

25:11.777 --> 25:13.110
JESSI: You're so good!

25:13.112 --> 25:14.395
CHRIS: Look at that fish
you just got!

25:14.397 --> 25:15.913
JESSI: Yeah!

25:15.915 --> 25:17.581
(laughing)

25:17.583 --> 25:19.316
CHRIS: Give it a whack,
really hard.

25:19.318 --> 25:20.183
(thud)

25:20.185 --> 25:21.118
Good job.

25:21.120 --> 25:24.588
JESSI: Oh, my gosh, fish.

25:24.590 --> 25:28.259
Yeah, Chris!

25:28.261 --> 25:30.661
Chris and I are
a fantastic team.

25:30.663 --> 25:34.932
One of these fish is gonna feed
Chris and I for almost a week.

25:34.934 --> 25:36.466
Thing is, is I want
to get more fish.

25:36.468 --> 25:38.936
I think it's time
to put in the fyke net.

25:38.938 --> 25:40.137
Cool.

25:40.139 --> 25:43.140
Take this...

25:43.142 --> 25:49.146
and one, two, three.

25:50.616 --> 25:51.949
See how it's nice?

25:51.951 --> 25:54.618
You can't see
the fyke net at all.

25:54.620 --> 25:57.688
It's completely submerged.

25:57.690 --> 26:01.692
It's perfectly positioned
for all the fish

26:01.694 --> 26:04.494
to come funneling in.

26:04.496 --> 26:06.563
And that's all you need.

26:06.565 --> 26:08.098
Great.

26:08.100 --> 26:12.636
♪ ♪

26:12.638 --> 26:15.038
JOHNNY: Subsistence
is a big part of my life.

26:15.040 --> 26:17.575
It's just part
of feeling free, living free,

26:17.577 --> 26:20.777
to go out into the wild
and to catch wild food.

26:20.779 --> 26:25.716
(water rushing)

26:25.718 --> 26:27.584
This right here
is the honey hole.

26:27.586 --> 26:33.590
♪ ♪

26:33.592 --> 26:35.960
It's my favorite place to come.

26:35.962 --> 26:37.728
You just catch netfuls of fish.

26:37.730 --> 26:39.129
They hang out in the pool

26:39.131 --> 26:41.932
and reserve their energy
to try to make it up.

26:41.934 --> 26:44.134
That's a tough waterfall
to make it up.

26:44.136 --> 26:45.335
Good luck to ya.

26:45.337 --> 26:48.405
Let's get fishing, Java.

26:48.407 --> 26:51.408
I would say over 90 percent
of my diet is meat,

26:51.410 --> 26:53.677
and it's all meat that I hunt.

